  "prompt": "Why Euler's Modified Method is created if there is already Euler's Method?",
  "response": "Euler's Modified Method (also known as the Improved Euler Method or Heun's Method) was developed to address some limitations of the standard Euler's Method. Here are the key reasons:\n\n1. Accuracy Improvement\n- Standard Euler's Method uses only one slope (derivative) at the beginning of the interval\n- Modified Euler's Method uses an average of two slopes, providing a more accurate approximation\n\n2. Error Reduction\n- Euler's Method has a local truncation error of O(h\u00b2)\n- Modified Euler's Method reduces this error to O(h\u00b3), making it more precise\n\n3. Computational Technique\n- Modified Method uses a predictor-corrector approach:\n  a) First, predict the next point using standard Euler's Method\n  b) Then, correct the slope using the predicted point\n- This averaging of slopes provides a better estimate of the solution\n\n4. Numerical Stability\n- More stable for solving differential equations, especially with larger step sizes\n- Less prone to accumulating significant errors over multiple iterations\n\nExample:\nStandard Euler: y(n+1) = y(n) + h * f(x(n), y(n))\nModified Euler: y(n+1) = y(n) + (h/2) * [f(x(n), y(n)) + f(x(n+1), y(n+1))]\n\nThese improvements make Modified Euler's Method more reliable for many numerical integration problems.",
